title: Introduction - Model Context Protocol
text:
Introduction - Model Context Protocol Model Context Protocol home page Version 2025-06-18 (latest) Search... ⌘ K GitHub Search... Navigation User Guide Introduction User Guide Introduction Quickstart Concepts Examples Tutorials FAQs Protocol Specification Key Changes Architecture Base Protocol Client Features Server Features Development Versioning Roadmap Contributing SDKs C# SDK Java SDK Kotlin SDK Python SDK Ruby SDK Swift SDK TypeScript SDK User Guide Copy page Introduction Get started with the Model Context Protocol (MCP) MCP is an open protocol that standardizes how applications provide context to LLMs. Think of MCP like a USB-C port for AI applications. Just as USB-C provides a standardized way to connect your devices to various peripherals and accessories, MCP provides a standardized way to connect AI models to different data sources and tools. ​ Why MCP? MCP helps you build agents and complex workflows on top of LLMs. LLMs frequently need to integrate with data and tools, and MCP provides: A growing list of pre-built integrations that your LLM can directly plug into The flexibility to switch between LLM providers and vendors Best practices for securing your data within your infrastructure ​ General architecture At its core, MCP follows a client-server architecture where a host application can connect to multiple servers: MCP Hosts : Programs like Claude Desktop, IDEs, or AI tools that want to access data through MCP MCP Clients : Protocol clients that maintain 1:1 connections with servers MCP Servers : Lightweight programs that each expose specific capabilities through the standardized Model Context Protocol Local Data Sources : Your computer’s files, databases, and services that MCP servers can securely access Remote Services : External systems available over the internet (e.g., through APIs) that MCP servers can connect to ​ Get started Choose the path that best fits your needs: ​ Quick Starts For Server Developers Get started building your own server to use in Claude for Desktop and other
clients For Client Developers Get started building your own client that can integrate with all MCP servers For Claude Desktop Users Get started using pre-built servers in Claude for Desktop ​ Examples Example Servers Check out our gallery of official MCP servers and implementations Example Clients View the list of clients that support MCP integrations ​ Tutorials Building MCP with LLMs Learn how to use LLMs like Claude to speed up your MCP development Debugging Guide Learn how to effectively debug MCP servers and integrations MCP Inspector Test and inspect your MCP servers with our interactive debugging tool MCP Workshop (Video, 2hr) ​ Explore MCP Dive deeper into MCP’s core concepts and capabilities: Core architecture Understand how MCP connects clients, servers, and LLMs Resources Expose data and content from your servers to LLMs Prompts Create reusable prompt templates and workflows Tools Enable LLMs to perform actions through your server Sampling Let your servers request completions from LLMs Transports Learn about MCP’s communication mechanism ​ Contributing Want to contribute? Check out our Contributing Guide to learn how you can help improve MCP. ​ Support and Feedback Here’s how to get help or provide feedback: For bug reports and feature requests related to the MCP specification, SDKs, or documentation (open source), please create a GitHub issue For discussions or Q&A about the MCP specification, use the specification discussions For discussions or Q&A about other MCP open source components, use the organization discussions For bug reports, feature requests, and questions related to Claude.app and claude.ai’s MCP integration, please see Anthropic’s guide on How to Get Support Was this page helpful? Yes No For Server Developers github On this page Why MCP? General architecture Get started Quick Starts Examples Tutorials Explore MCP Contributing Support and Feedback Assistant Responses are generated using AI and may contain mistakes.

clients For Client Developers Get started building your own client that can integrate with all MCP servers For Claude Desktop Users Get started using pre-built servers in Claude for Desktop ​ Examples Example Servers Check out our gallery of official MCP servers and implementations Example Clients View the list of clients that support MCP integrations ​ Tutorials Building MCP with LLMs Learn how to use LLMs like Claude to speed up your MCP development Debugging Guide Learn how to effectively debug MCP servers and integrations MCP Inspector Test and inspect your MCP servers with our interactive debugging tool MCP Workshop (Video, 2hr) ​ Explore MCP Dive deeper into MCP’s core concepts and capabilities: Core architecture Understand how MCP connects clients, servers, and LLMs Resources Expose data and content from your servers to LLMs Prompts Create reusable prompt templates and workflows Tools Enable LLMs to perform actions through your server Sampling Let your servers request completions from LLMs Transports Learn about MCP’s communication mechanism ​ Contributing Want to contribute? Check out our Contributing Guide to learn how you can help improve MCP. ​ Support and Feedback Here’s how to get help or provide feedback: For bug reports and feature requests related to the MCP specification, SDKs, or documentation (open source), please create a GitHub issue For discussions or Q&A about the MCP specification, use the specification discussions For discussions or Q&A about other MCP open source components, use the organization discussions For bug reports, feature requests, and questions related to Claude.app and claude.ai’s MCP integration, please see Anthropic’s guide on How to Get Support Was this page helpful? Start chatting through AI. Your personal AI agent works invisibly in the background, making every message you send more thoughtful, clear, and kind. You're still talking to real people — just with a better version of yourself. "Hey! I found a few amazing Italian spots in Kendall. Want to try one this weekend?" Your Agent • now Enhanced with context Still your voice Your agent amplifies your intent without changing your personality. It removes friction while keeping you in control. Preserves your communication style Adds helpful context Always sounds natural Handling delays gracefully No more awkwardness Transform rushed responses into thoughtful messages that show you care. Message Quality 95% Before "Sorry, forgot to text back" After "Just saw this — sorry for the delay! What do you think about the idea you shared?" +73% more engaging For every conversation Family Coordinate holidays, share updates, stay connected across time zones. "Help me write a nice message to grandma about visiting" Work Collaborate with colleagues, schedule meetings, handle feedback diplomatically. "Respond to this feedback diplomatically but firmly" Friends Make weekend plans, share recommendations, organize group activities. "Find a fun activity for 6 people this Saturday" Dating Craft thoughtful messages, plan dates, navigate early conversations. "Suggest a creative second date idea" Living Coordinate chores, share expenses, address household issues tactfully. "Split utilities without sounding passive-aggressive" Study Organize study sessions, share resources, explain complex topics. "Explain this concept clearly to my study group" Built for tomorrow Built on advanced agent communication protocols. Real-time collaboration between humans and AI agents. No app switching. No perfect prompts. Just ask, drag, and go. Real-time collaboration Instant AI assistance as you type Privacy-first Your data stays encrypted & secure Your voice, amplified Still you, just more thoughtful Ready? text: NANDA - The Internet of AI Agents Skip to main content MIT Decentralized AI Features Learn More Partners Working Groups Contact Team May 13th Summit Videos NANDA: The Internet of AI Agents Pioneering the Future of Decentralized Intelligence Imagine billions of specialized AI agents collaborating across a decentralized architecture. Each performs discrete functions while communicating seamlessly, navigating autonomously, socializing, learning, earning and transacting on our behalf. NANDA Registry Documentation NANDA Host Join the Ecosystem View Events Calendar NANDA Ecosystem NANDA (Networked Agents And Decentralized AI) builds on Anthropic's Model Context Protocol (MCP) to create a true Internet of AI Agents. While MCP provides standardized interaction between AI agents, tools and resources, NANDA adds the critical infrastructure needed for distributed agent intelligence at scale. NANDA Discovery Mechanisms for agents to find each other in the network. Search Functionality Systems for querying distributed knowledge across agent networks. Authentication Secure verification protocols for trustworthy agent interactions. Trace Verifiable agent-to-agent exchange accountability. Components Protocol Layer Agent-to-agent protocol providing the foundation for AI communication. Developer Tools Services for developers to build on NANDA ecosystem. Infrastructure Layer Registry of agents, resources and tools, database of agentic interactions. Applications Third-party integrations with client and server SDKs, registries, databases and protocol. Learn More Official Website Explore the MIT Decentralized AI program Visit Website Perspective Paper Read about decentralized AI technology Download PDF Walkthrough Video Add your MCP server to NANDA Registry Watch Video Research Hub Discover research at MIT Media Lab Explore Research Partnership Opportunities Host Registry Host a copy of NANDA registry at your organization to help scale to growing number of users and queries. Connect Your API or Launch App Connect your API to a lightweight NANDA server OR connect your app/tool to a lightweight NANDA server. Contribute to Open Source Production-grade deployment architecture, implementation assistance and maintenance over time. Comprehensive unit testing. NANDA Servers on Github Global Collaboration Network Hover over the dots to see our Founding Node Members. Thai Cobra Scorpion Whiskey, often referred to as “Snake Whiskey,” is a type of spirit found in Southeast Asia, particularly in Thailand and Vietnam. This whiskey is notable for containing either a whole snake, scorpion, or both, in the bottle. The snakes are often venomous, like cobras, and the belief is that their venom is neutralized by the ethanol in the whiskey. While none of these claims have been tested and verified by BarWarriors, thousands of sailors and marines have tasted this beast and survived. Table of Contents The Tradition and History How Did They Get The Cobra In The Bottle? The Making of Cobra Whiskey Medicinal Claims and Cultural Significance Controversies and Concerns The Tradition and History While it’s often referred to as “Snake Wine,” “Snake Whiskey,” and “Cobra Whiskey,” there isn’t a traditional name for the spirit. It’s known solely by descriptive terms. And in another weird twist, despite the liquor commonly infusing a whole snake in the bottle, using a cobra isn’t a requirement. In fact, medicinal liquors of this type usually feature a variety of regional animals and insects. This tradition of infusing alcohol with animals or insects dates back centuries in Asia. These practices are often rooted in traditional medicine systems, like Traditional Chinese Medicine and similar local practices in Vietnam and Thailand. In many Asian cultures, snakes are seen as powerful and potent creatures. The belief is that the essence and characteristics of these animals is infused into the liquor, imparting both flavor and therapeutic properties. By infusing the snake, it’s a way of harnessing its power. It also serves as a symbol of bravery and fearlessness. How Did They Get The Cobra In The Bottle? The Making of Cobra Whiskey The making of Cobra Whiskey involves a process that’s as intriguing as the drink itself. Here’s an overview of how it’s typically made: Selection of the Snake and/or Scorpion: The snakes used are usually venomous, such as cobras, while the scorpions are typically large and potent. They are chosen based on local beliefs about the medicinal properties they possess. The animals are often farmed or captured specifically for this purpose. Neutralization of the Venom: The venom of these creatures is protein-based, which means it’s rendered inactive by the ethanol in the whiskey—we’ve never been so happy to drink ethanol in our lives! This supposedly makes the drink safe to consume, as the venom is no longer poisonous after this process. Preparation of the Snake or Scorpion: The snake or scorpion is often killed just before the preparation. Then they are sometimes sewn or positioned into a threatening pose (like a cobra with its hood expanded) before being placed in the bottle. This is partly for the visual effect and to adhere to the belief that the animal’s strength and characteristics are transferred to the drink. Insertion into the Bottle: The snake or scorpion is then inserted into the bottle. For larger bottles, this is relatively straightforward, but with smaller bottles, this can require skill and sometimes involves dislocating or bending the snake to fit. Infusion: The bottle is then filled with whiskey or rice wine. The spirit used is typically a strong, clear grain alcohol, which is necessary to preserve the snake or scorpion and to ensure the venom is neutralized. Additional Ingredients: Sometimes herbs, spices, or other medicinal ingredients are added to the whiskey to enhance its flavor and its supposed health benefits. Aging: The whiskey is then left to ferment from several months to many years. During this time, it is believed that the essence and the supposed medicinal and virility-enhancing properties of the snake or scorpion infuse into the liquor. Medicinal Claims and Cultural Significance Cobra whiskey is said to possess various health benefits according to traditional beliefs. These include: Enhancing Virility: It’s often believed to act as an aphrodisiac and improve sexual performance. Some people who drink it experience numbing in their, er, extremities. Boosting Vitality: The whiskey is thought to imbue the drinker with the cobra’s strength and agility. Pain Relief: Some claim it can relieve different forms of pain and aches. Curing Hair Loss: In some traditions, it’s thought to promote hair growth or prevent hair loss. Improving Vision: There are claims that it can enhance eyesight, drawing a parallel to the keen vision of snakes. Controversies and Concerns It’s important to approach Snake or Scorpion Whiskey with caution, especially considering the potential health risks and the ethical considerations regarding

title: intfloat/multilingual-e5-large-instruct · Hugging Face
text:
intfloat/multilingual-e5-large-instruct · Hugging Face Hugging Face Models Datasets Spaces Community Docs Enterprise Pricing Log In Sign Up intfloat / multilingual-e5-large-instruct like 522 Feature Extraction sentence-transformers ONNX Safetensors Transformers 94 languages xlm-roberta mteb Eval Results text-embeddings-inference arxiv: 4 papers License: mit Model card Files Files and versions Community 26 Train Deploy Use this model Multilingual-E5-large-instruct Usage Transformers Sentence Transformers Infinity Supported Languages Training Details MTEB Benchmark Evaluation FAQ Citation Limitations Multilingual-E5-large-instruct Multilingual E5 Text Embeddings: A Technical Report .
Liang Wang, Nan Yang, Xiaolong Huang, Linjun Yang, Rangan Majumder, Furu Wei, arXiv 2024 This model has 24 layers and the embedding size is 1024. Usage Below are examples to encode queries and passages from the MS-MARCO passage ranking dataset. Transformers import torch.nn.functional as F from torch import Tensor from transformers import AutoTokenizer, AutoModel def average_pool ( last_hidden_states: Tensor, attention_mask: Tensor ) -> Tensor:
    last_hidden = last_hidden_states.masked_fill(~attention_mask[..., None ]. bool (), 0.0 ) return last_hidden. sum (dim= 1 ) / attention_mask. sum (dim= 1 )[..., None ] def get_detailed_instruct ( task_description: str , query: str ) -> str : return f'Instruct: {task_description} \nQuery: {query} ' # Each query must come with a one-sentence instruction that describes the task task = 'Given a web search query, retrieve relevant passages that answer the query' queries = [
    get_detailed_instruct(task, 'how much protein should a female eat' ),
    get_detailed_instruct(task, '南瓜的家常做法' )
] # No need to add instruction for retrieval documents documents = [ "As a general guideline, the CDC's average requirement of protein for women ages 19 to 70 is 46 grams per day. But, as you can see from this chart, you'll need to increase that if you're expecting or training for a marathon. Check out the chart below to see how much protein you should be eating each day." , "1.清炒南瓜丝 原料:嫩南瓜半个 调料:葱、盐、白糖、鸡精 做法: 1、南瓜用刀薄薄的削去表面一层皮,用勺子刮去瓤 2、擦成细丝(没有擦菜板就用刀慢慢切成细丝) 3、锅烧热放油,入葱花煸出香味 4、入南瓜丝快速翻炒一分钟左右,放盐、一点白糖和鸡精调味出锅 2.香葱炒南瓜 原料:南瓜1只 调料:香葱、蒜末、橄榄油、盐 做法: 1、将南瓜去皮,切成片 2、油锅8成热后,将蒜末放入爆香 3、爆香后,将南瓜片放入,翻炒 4、在翻炒的同时,可以不时地往锅里加水,但不要太多 5、放入盐,炒匀 6、南瓜差不多软和绵了之后,就可以关火 7、撒入香葱,即可出锅" ]
input_texts = queries + documents

tokenizer = AutoTokenizer.from_pretrained( 'intfloat/multilingual-e5-large-instruct' )
model = AutoModel.from_pretrained( 'intfloat/multilingual-e5-large-instruct' ) # Tokenize the input texts batch_dict = tokenizer(input_texts, max_length= 512 , padding= True , truncation= True , return_tensors= 'pt' )

outputs = model(**batch_dict)
embeddings = average_pool(outputs.last_hidden_state, batch_dict[ 'attention_mask' ]) # normalize embeddings embeddings = F.normalize(embeddings, p= 2 , dim= 1 )
scores = (embeddings[: 2 ] @ embeddings[ 2 :].T) * 100 print (scores.tolist()) # => [[91.92852783203125, 67.580322265625], [70.3814468383789, 92.1330795288086]] Sentence Transformers from sentence_transformers import SentenceTransformer def get_detailed_instruct ( task_description: str , query: str ) -> str : return f'Instruct: {task_description} \nQuery: {query} ' # Each query must come with a one-sentence instruction that describes the task task = 'Given a web search query, retrieve relevant passages that answer the query' queries = [
    get_detailed_instruct(task, 'how much protein should a female eat' ),
    get_detailed_instruct(task, '南瓜的家常做法' )
] # No need to add instruction for retrieval documents documents = [ "As a general guideline, the CDC's average requirement of protein for women ages 19 to 70 is 46 grams per day. But, as you can see from this chart, you'll need to increase that if you're expecting or training for a marathon. Check out the chart below to see how much protein you should be eating each day." , "1.清炒南瓜丝 原料:嫩南瓜半个 调料:葱、盐、白糖、鸡精 做法: 1、南瓜用刀薄薄的削去表面一层皮,用勺子刮去瓤 2、擦成细丝(没有擦菜板就用刀慢慢切成细丝) 3、锅烧热放油,入葱花煸出香味 4、入南瓜丝快速翻炒一分钟左右,放盐、一点白糖和鸡精调味出锅 2.香葱炒南瓜 原料:南瓜1只 调料:香葱、蒜末、橄榄油、盐 做法: 1、将南瓜去皮,切成片 2、油锅8成热后,将蒜末放入爆香 3、爆香后,将南瓜片放入,翻炒 4、在翻炒的同时,可以不时地往锅里加水,但不要太多 5、放入盐,炒匀 6、南瓜差不多软和绵了之后,就可以关火 7、撒入香葱,即可出锅" ]
input_texts = queries + documents

model = SentenceTransformer( 'intfloat/multilingual-e5-large-instruct' )

embeddings = model.encode(input_texts, convert_to_tensor= True , normalize_embeddings= True )
scores = (embeddings[: 2 ] @ embeddings[ 2 :].T) * 100 print (scores.tolist()) # [[91.92853546142578, 67.5802993774414], [70.38143157958984, 92.13307189941406]] Infinity Usage with Infinity : docker run --gpus all -v $PWD /data:/app/.cache -e HF_TOKEN= $HF_TOKEN -p "7997" : "7997" \
